      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Ugly Charge Of Anti-Semitism</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Rabbi Moshe Kwalbrun letter, commenting on July 18 article, dismisses allegations of anti-Semitism made against Hillary Rodham Clinton in book by Paul and Mary Fray (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Accusation Mrs. Clinton Deems Too Crucial to Ignore'' (news article, July 18):</p>
        <p>On July 13, Hillary Rodham Clinton addressed a standing-room audience at Bell Park Jewish Center, where I am a rabbi. It was a nonpartisan, but educational and informative, gathering.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''An Accusation Mrs. Clinton Deems Too Crucial to Ignore'' (news article, July 18):</p>
        <p>On July 13, Hillary Rodham Clinton addressed a standing-room audience at Bell Park Jewish Center, where I am a rabbi. It was a nonpartisan, but educational and informative, gathering.</p>
        <p>To listen to Mrs. Clinton, and to judge from her past record, it would be most difficult to give credence to the accusations maligning her as an anti-Semite.</p>
        <p>Teachings of our sages in Judaism make it clear that witnesses who stand to benefit personally by their allegations against the accused cannot be deemed acceptable.</p>
        <p>One would wish to understand why such a scurrilous ad hominem accusation was brought to light so many years later.</p>
        <p>MOSHE KWALBRUN  Queens Village, Queens, July 19, 2000</p>
      </block>
